.SH "NAME"
.IX Header "NAME"
encode_base64 \- Encode string using base64 encoding
.PP
decode_base64 \- Decode base64 string
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.PP
.Vb 1
\& use MIME::Base64;
.Ve
.Vb 2
\& $encoded = encode_base64('Aladdin:open sesame');
\& $decoded = decode_base64($encoded);
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module provides functions to encode and decode strings into the
Base64 encoding specified in RFC 1521 \- \fIMIME (Multipurpose Internet
Mail Extensions)\fR. The Base64 encoding is designed to represent
arbitrary sequences of octets in a form that need not be humanly
readable. A 65-character subset ([A\-Za-z0-9+/=]) of US\-ASCII is used,
enabling 6 bits to be represented per printable character.
.PP
RFC 1521 says that the encoded bytes must be represented in lines of
no more than 76 characters each.  The second argument to
\fIencode_base64()\fR is the line ending sequence to use. It defaults to
\f(CW"\en"\fR.  Use an empty string as second argument if you do not want
the encoded string broken into lines.
.PP
If you prefer not to import these routines into your namespace you can
call them as:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&  use MIME::Base64 ();
\&  $encoded = MIME::Base64::encode('Aladdin:open sesame');
\&  $decoded = MIME::Base64::decode($encoded);
.Ve
